tle><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F04237X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Albeit the extensive attention paid to South East Europe in the 1990s important academic and policy-relevant conclusions went missing. This is becoming increasingly obvious as instability and crisis returns to the region with potentially explosive consequences. Through the use of rich empirical material from the Bosnian war as well as relevant on site professional experience from the post-war state-building efforts the project aims at contributing to a comprehensive understanding of the post-conflict societies in the Balkans. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project focus will be at three different levels: &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>the academic debates on political competition during conflict, civic and moderate alternatives to extremism, and externally promoted state-building,&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the policy debates on the above as well as on the problem of Islamist radicalism, &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the processes of truth recovery and reconciliation in Bosnia. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>Among others, conclusions will be drawn from the complex socio-political developments that enabled the emergence and survival of relatively moderate political alternatives in wartime Bosnia as well as from Muslim pathways to moderation and radicalisation. Apart from academic publications, research findings will be disseminated through a workshop on political competition during conflict, a policy paper, and a Truth &amp;amp; Reconciliation workshop for local participants in Bosnia. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>70559</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/F04237X/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5D762B83-597E-4E91-B2F7-04CBB955175C</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Pol. sci. &amp; internat. studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>32A0976A-B577-4829-A940-9AB6B148F977</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text